Food Insecurity and Health Indicators in MN Counties

Emma Holden

2025-04-12

Introduction:

Background

Food insecurity is something that affects many people all around us and in our local communities. When someone doesnt know where their next meal is coming from, or how/if theyre going to secure that basic need, then they are experiencing food insecurity. For this project I wanted to visually map the rates of food insecurity across MN counties, to then compare these rates with diet-related health outcomes, and to look into some preventative factors for local government and outreach programs to focus on in order to help improve the health of the community at large.

Data

The dataset I will be referring to in this project is from CDC PLACES: Local Data for Better Health, County Data 2024 release. This dataset is collected and hosted by the United States Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and is available on their website here.

According to the CDC, 40 of the health measures were collected by a Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System, the US Census decennial population survey, and Census annual county population estimates. The Places website describes this data as obtained by small-area estimation methods. The other 9 measures are social determinants of health which were collected by the American Community Surveys 5-year estimates.

For map data, I will be using the census tract data available through an ArcGIS application here.

places <- read_csv("PLACES__Local_Data_for_Better_Health__County_Data_2024_release_20250221.csv") #cdc places dataset
places_MN_aged <- places %>% 
  filter(StateAbbr=="MN"& Data_Value_Type=="Age-adjusted prevalence") #by age-adjusted prevalence

map_MN <- read_sf("cb_2023_27_tract_500k.shp") #map data

Data Dictionary

MeasureId Measure
DIABETES Diagnosed Diabetes among adults
CHD Coronary Heart Disease among adults
COPD Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease among adults
STROKE Stroke among adults
BPHIGH High blood pressure among adults
FOODINSECU Food insecurity in the past 12 months among adults
FOODSTAMP Received food stamps in the past 12 months among adults
CHOLSCREEN Rate of Cholesterol Screening among adults

Choosing a Preventative Measure

Going into this project, I had already chosen food insecurity and diabetes as measures of interest, but I knew I wanted at least one preventative measure to examine for potential areas of change. Initially, I had looked at rates of recieving foodstamps, but that measure is only observed in the population of individuals already experiencing food insecurity leading to a false-positive correlation.

To choose a different preventative measure, I created a scatterplot of food insecurity by measures labeled as preventative health measures in the CDC dataset (CategoryID of PREVENT). I filtered the measures visually by color, and with regression lines for each. I made a second scatterplot replacing food insecurity with diabetes rates, and compared the two visualizations below:

prevention<- places_MN_aged%>%
  filter(CategoryID=="PREVENT"| MeasureId=="FOODINSECU" |MeasureId=="DIABETES")%>%
  select(LocationName, Data_Value, MeasureId) #creating a new dataframe with preventative measures, food insecurity, and diabetes

testing_foodinsecu<- prevention%>%
  filter(MeasureId=="FOODINSECU")%>%
  rename("food_insecurity"= Data_Value)%>%
  select(food_insecurity, LocationName)  #renaming for clarity

testing_diabetes<- prevention%>%
  filter(MeasureId=="DIABETES")%>%
  rename("diabetes_rates"= Data_Value)%>%
  select(diabetes_rates, LocationName)

prevention<- left_join(prevention, testing_foodinsecu, by='LocationName')
prevention<- left_join(prevention, testing_diabetes, by='LocationName')

prevention<- prevention%>%
  filter(MeasureId=="ACCESS2" | MeasureId== "BPMED"|
           MeasureId=="CHECKUP" | MeasureId=="COLON_SCREEN" |
           MeasureId=="DENTAL" | MeasureId=="CHOLSCREEN" |
           MeasureId=="MAMMOUSE")
gg_prev_food<- prevention%>%  #plotting food insecurity by prevention measures
  ggplot(aes(x=Data_Value, y=food_insecurity, color=MeasureId, alpha=0.2))+
  geom_point()+
  guides(alpha= "none")+
  geom_smooth(method = lm, se=FALSE)

gg_prev_diab<-  prevention%>%  #plotting diabetes by prevention measures
  ggplot(aes(x=Data_Value, y=diabetes_rates, color=MeasureId, alpha=0.2))+
  geom_point()+
  guides(alpha= "none")+
  geom_smooth(method = lm, se=FALSE)

grid.arrange(gg_prev_food, gg_prev_diab, ncol=1, nrow=2)  #arranging the two together

Initially I was interested in access to healthcare (ACCESSS2) due to the positive correlation, however thats a very broad measure that encompasses a ton of issues and barriers to access. The only other positive correlation was taking blood pressure meds to reduce blood pressure (BPMED), but that could have complications later if I compared the heart health measures I was considering for a visualization. I was also interested in the negative slope of cholesterol screening, and the potential for meaningful change that could be brought by making cholesterol screening more accessible to all.

Data Cleaning

The next step, after initial cleaning and deciding on my measures, was to filter the data to just these measures in wide form. I kept the original long form for later, in case I would need to refer back to it.

long_places_MN_aged<- places_MN_aged%>%
  filter(MeasureId == 'DIABETES' | MeasureId == 'CHD' | 
           MeasureId == 'COPD' | MeasureId == 'STROKE' |
           MeasureId == 'BPHIGH' | MeasureId == 'FOODINSECU' |
           MeasureId == 'FOODSTAMP' | MeasureId =='CHOLSCREEN')%>%   #choosing measures
  select(LocationName, TotalPop18plus, Measure, Geolocation,
         Low_Confidence_Limit, High_Confidence_Limit, Data_Value)   #kept the confidence limits in the long form, in case I wanted to make a bar graph later


wide_places_MN_aged <- long_places_MN_aged %>%
  pivot_wider(id_cols = LocationName,
              names_from = Measure, 
              values_from = Data_Value)  #pivoted wider for use in analysis

The next step was to rename the columns back to their MeasureIds (for convenience), I did this instead of initially selecting by MeasureId in cleaning stage, because some measures had shared IDs (the HLTHSTAT ones) and I wanted to be very careful to avoid any potential issues from this. This way I could refer back to this code chunk instead of consulting the data dictionary too.

wide_places_MN_aged <- wide_places_MN_aged%>%
  rename("COPD"=`Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease among adults`) %>%
  rename("CHD"= `Coronary heart disease among adults`) %>%
  rename("BPHIGH"= `High blood pressure among adults`)%>%
  rename("STROKE"= `Stroke among adults`)%>%
  rename("DIABETES"= `Diagnosed diabetes among adults`)%>%
  rename("FOODINSECU"= `Food insecurity in the past 12 months among adults`)%>%
  rename("CHOLSCREEN"= `Cholesterol screening among adults`)%>%
  rename("FOODSTAMP"= `Received food stamps in the past 12 months among adults`)

I also created a mutation in a new column for a ratio between rates of diabetes and food insecurity. I divided diabetes by food insecurity. This ratio is for later, when I compared the prevalence of these issues.

wide_places_MN_aged<- wide_places_MN_aged%>% #creating mutation
  mutate(diabetes_foodinsecu_ratio= 
           (DIABETES/FOODINSECU))

I joined the ArcGIS map data .shp file to my wide dataset into a new dataframe for later visualizations, so the dataframe map_MN is optimized for map visuals and wide_places_MN_aged is optimized for correlations.

#Creating a new column in wide data table with location formatted same as .shp file
wide_places_MN_aged<- wide_places_MN_aged %>% 
  mutate(NAMELSADCO = 
           str_c(LocationName, " County"))  #added this string to end so that the Location Name values would be "x County" instead of "X", as NAMELSADCO in .shp file includes " County" after each county name

map_MN<- left_join(map_MN, wide_places_MN_aged, by='NAMELSADCO') #joining back by location

adult_pop_df<- places_MN_aged%>%
  mutate(NAMELSADCO = str_c(LocationName, " County"))%>%
    select(NAMELSADCO, TotalPop18plus)
#adding a column for adult population for later reference

map_MN<- left_join(map_MN, adult_pop_df, by='NAMELSADCO') #joining by location

Summary Stats:

Another visual representation of the skew of the above distribution is with a summary, which shows that the minimum (or point where theres the most food insecurity compared to diabetes) is much further from the point of these rates being equal (1), than the maximum (or point where theres the most diabetes compared to food insecurity). This also shows that the Median, Mean, and even 3rd quartile are all under 1; ie. theres more food insecurity overall than there is diabetes in MN counties.

summary(wide_places_MN_aged$diabetes_foodinsecu_ratio) #summary is filtered to just be for this ratio in the wide places dataset
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.5588  0.8077  0.8791  0.8888  0.9735  1.2024

Protective Factors

Foodstamps:

Initially, I tried comparing foodstamps as a protective factor. I hypothesized that foodstamps would decrease food insecurity, and possibly show a decrease in diabetes. However, this hypothesis proved to be unsuitable for the dataset due to foodstamp eligibility being dependent on food insecurity. I visualized the relationships between foodstamps and food insecurity, and between foodstamps and diabetes, and noted this false-positive relationship.

gg_stamp_foodinsecu<- map_MN%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = FOODSTAMP, y=FOODINSECU)) +
  geom_point(color="darkgreen", size=3)+
  theme_tufte()+
  geom_smooth(method=lm, se=FALSE, color="lightgreen", size=2)

gg_stamp_diabetes<- map_MN%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = FOODSTAMP, y=DIABETES)) +
  geom_point(color="darkblue", size=3)+
  theme_tufte()+
  geom_smooth(method=lm, se=FALSE, color="skyblue", size=2)

I took a closer look at the foodstamp/diabetes correlation and the food insecurity/diabetes correlation to compare:

grid.arrange(gg_stamp_diabetes, gg_insecu_diabetes, ncol=2, nrow=1)

They appear as nearly the same line.

Cholesterol Screening:

I ran a correlation matrix below to see how strong those relationships truly are:

chol_matrix <- cor(wide_places_MN_aged[, c("FOODINSECU", "DIABETES" ,"CHOLSCREEN")])
print(chol_matrix)

cor.test(wide_places_MN_aged$FOODINSECU, wide_places_MN_aged$DIABETES)

Conclusion and Recommendations

Based on this project, I would make the following recommendations:

Increase accessibility to cholesterol screening. More research is recommended into why counties may have lower rates of cholesterol screening, and how it specifically relates (is it health access by income? is it diet-choices, made difficult by food insecurity? Does simple awareness have an impact without any other preventative factors? Either way, access would benefit community health).

Further research into relationship between diabetes and food insecurity. Does providing food insecurity support lower rates of diabetes in MN counties? Does providing diabetes support decrease rates of food insecurity? What are the counties with the lowest rates of these things doing to maintain these low rates?

As individuals, we can volunteer with local community organizations to help others in our community have better access to nutritional food.

As organized community, we can target aid programs to counties that experience the highest rates of food insecurity for more immediate support.

This brings us to our last point

Whats the deal with Mahnomen County?

Earlier, we noted that Mahnomen County has abnormally high food insecurity and diabetes rates. I wanted to see if this was an issue with the data, or a genuine problem faced by the people living there. First, I went back to my initial data cleaning and checked to see if it was an error in the age-adjusted values. I tested the crude data from the initial places dataset, for top 5 highest diabetes rates and food insecurity rates in order to see if Mahnomen was an outlier there as well.

In the crude dataset, Mahnomen County also has the highest rates of these variables.

crude_test <- places %>% 
  filter(StateAbbr=="MN"& Data_Value_Type=="Crude prevalence") #creating crude dataframe

long_crude<- crude_test%>%
  filter(MeasureId == 'DIABETES' | MeasureId == 'CHD' | 
           MeasureId == 'COPD' | MeasureId == 'STROKE' |
           MeasureId == 'BPHIGH' | MeasureId == 'FOODINSECU' |
           MeasureId == 'FOODSTAMP' | MeasureId =='CHOLSCREEN')%>%
  select(LocationName, TotalPop18plus, Measure, Geolocation,
         Low_Confidence_Limit, High_Confidence_Limit, Data_Value)


wide_crude <- long_crude %>%
  pivot_wider(id_cols = LocationName,
              names_from = Measure, 
              values_from = Data_Value)

wide_crude%>%
  arrange(desc(`Food insecurity in the past 12 months among adults`))%>%
  select(`Food insecurity in the past 12 months among adults`, LocationName)%>%
  head(5)  #getting highest food insecu rates

I did some further research, comparing to the national average, and then comparing to the difference betwen Mahnomen Countys rate and the MN state average. Findings indicated that even compared to these averages, Mahnomen Countys rates of 23.8% of adults reporting food insecurity and 13.3% of adults diagnosed with diabetes are high:

state_avg<- places%>%
  filter(Data_Value_Type=="Age-adjusted prevalence")%>%

## 1 DIABETES             11.1
## 2 FOODINSECU           16.4

I questioned whether the CDC Places dataset could have been erroneous, and found a secondary source. According to the data over at Feeding America, Mahnomen county only had a food insecurity rate of 13% in 2021, which, also according to them, is still the highest in the state.

Instead focusing my research on the location itself, I found that Mahnomen county is entirely encompassed by Gaa-Waabaabiganikaag, or White Earth Nation, which also extends partially into Clearwater and Becker counties. It is the only county in MN entirely encapsulated by a Native American reservation, although not the only First Nations community in MN.

Given this additional perspective I would also recommend further research into the rates of food insecurity in Native American reservations here in MN, as well as reaching out to food shelves and local community organizers in these areas in order to gain a better understanding of the factors that may be contributing to this rate.
